e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.111a35ed-e180-4b33-bbdb-97152c4f5dfb.prompt=Password\: e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.2723b3d0-f0af-48d8-8b0c-7673f78dbf85.prompt=HostName\: e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.2ca064be-85ba-435d-a7f2-76131354ace3.prompt=Password\: e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.31a96110-32ec-45bd-85f1-fd1776b1e525.description=
The operation runs a SSH command on the host.

Inputs\:
    host - Hostname or ip address.
    port - The port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input (in a syntax like host\:port), if this exists.
    command - The command to execute.
    arguments - The arguments to pass to the command.
    pty - Whether to use pty.
Valid values\: true, false. 
Default value\: false.
    privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file on the RAS host. The private key file must be in OpenSSH format.
    username - Username to connect as.
    password - Password of user. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000 ( 90 seconds ).
    characterSet - The character encoding used for input stream encoding from the target machine. 
Valid values\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8.  
Default value\: UTF-8. 
    closeSession - If "false" the ssh session will be cached for future calls of this operation during the life of the flow. If "true" the ssh session used by this operation will be closed.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: true.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the STDERR of the command if something went wrong or STDOUT otherwise.
    STDERR - The STDERR of the command.
    STDOUT - The STDOUT of the command.
    exitStatus - Every command returns an exit status (sometimes referred to as a return status or exit code). A successful command returns a 0, while an unsuccessful one returns a non-zero value that usually can be interpreted as an error code.

Responses\:
    success - The command was executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed.

Notes\:
1. If the SSH session is cached then only the connection is kept and not the context (variables) represented by SSH channel.
2. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.31c95e79-397b-411b-a0b6-3ac0be3dd763.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.

e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.bdf41309-b2d0-41ae-af5c-97fa43ceb0d7.prompt=Password\: e5c1b8b8-5f62-40a9-b0b9-107f4eb0a5e3.d633e122-1427-4ff5-8f47-d54e337c1cb5.description=
Creates a SSH Shell session to be used by multiple SSH Shell operations.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname/IP address of the remote machine.
    port - The port number for SSH protocol.
Default value\: 22
    username - Name of the account on the remote machine.
    password - The password for the username. When using a private key file or a private key string, this input will be used as the passphrase for the file or string. For security reasons it is recommend to provide this input and protect the private key when using the 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the remote machine.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    privateKeyData – A string representing the private key (OpenSSH type) used for authenticating the user. This string is usually the content of a private key file. The 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs are mutually exclusive. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommend to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. 
Valid values\:  
allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. 
strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. 
add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. 
Default value\: strict
    allowedCiphers - A comma separated list of ciphers that will be used in the client-server handshake mechanism when the connection is created. Check the notes section for security concerns regarding your choice of ciphers. The default value will be used even if the input is not added to the operation.
Default value\: aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc,3des-ctr,3des-cbc,blowfish-cbc,aes192-ctr,aes192-cbc,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc
    connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made.
Default value\: 10000
    useGlobalContext -  Specifies whether to enable the session sharing into the subflows.
Valid values\: false, true 
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - The newly created sessionId.
    sessionId - The ssh session identifier to be used for SSH Shell and SSH Shell Logoff operations.  This session identifier can only be used in the flow run context that it is created in. Multiple ssh shell sessions can be created and distinguished by assigning this sessionId to unique flow variables.
    TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out.

Responses\:
    success - SSH shell session and sessionId successfully created.
    failure - An error occurred while attempting to create the ssh shell session.

Notes\:
1. Hidden inputs\:
    knownHostsPath -  Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server.
Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts
Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts
2. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
3. The operation supports connections through HTTP proxy with username and password authentication.
4. For security reasons, HPE does not recommend the use of outdated or vulnerable ciphers. Therefore "arcfour" cihpers should be avoided because they do not provide confidentiality for data in transit and using them can lead to information leakage.
Arcfour is vulnerable to the following attacks\: Fluhrer, Mantin and Shamir attack, Klein's attack, Royal Holloway attack, Bar-mitzvah attack and NOMORE attack.
